---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<BaseLayout
  title="The 2018-2022 mandate · Riksdag Revealed"
  description="Sweden's 2018-2022 Riksdag mandate read with the same methodology as the 2022-2026 piece. The chamber before Tidö: red-green cabinet, Centerpartiet support, Sverigedemokraterna on its own arm."
>
  <article class="container">
    <header class="article-hero">
      <p class="byline">Riksdag Revealed · The 2018-22 mandate</p>
      <h1>The chamber before Tidö</h1>
      <p class="lede">
        Sweden's 2018-2022 Riksdag mandate, read with the same data
        sources and the same methodology used for the 2022-2026 piece.
        The figures use unified topic identifiers so they are
        directly comparable to the equivalents in the 2022-2026
        article and in the longitudinal overview.
      </p>
    </header>

    <p>
      The 2018 election produced a Riksdag with no parliamentary
      majority for either of the two traditional blocs. After four
      months of negotiations, the Löfven II cabinet was formed by
      Socialdemokraterna and Miljöpartiet on the basis of the
      January Agreement, a written deal with Centerpartiet and
      Liberalerna that exchanged confidence-and-supply support for
      a set of policy commitments. Moderaterna, Kristdemokraterna
      and Sverigedemokraterna were the opposition for most of the
      mandate. Liberalerna left the January Agreement in 2021;
      Miljöpartiet left the cabinet in 2021. The Magdalena Andersson
      cabinet replaced Löfven II in late 2021. The mandate ended
      with the September 2022 election.
    </p>

    <p>
      This was therefore not a single-government mandate, and the
      bloc structure changed substantively during the four-year
      window. The figures below average over the whole mandate
      unless explicitly broken down by riksmöte. Where year-by-year
      structure matters, it is shown separately.
    </p>

    <h2>The chamber map</h2>

    <p>
      Every chamber vote of the mandate, member by member,
      projected into two dimensions through PCA on the
      444-by-3,203 vote matrix.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/54_per_mandate_centroid_maps.png`} alt="Side-by-side per-mandate centroid maps" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Left: the 2018-22 chamber map. Right: 2022-26 for comparison.
        In 2018-22, Sverigedemokraterna sits on its own arm at PC2
        near +15, far from any other party. M and KD are together on
        the bottom-left. C and L cluster in the middle. S, V and MP
        cluster on the top-right.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Three patterns are visible in the 2018-22 panel that do not
      appear in the 2022-26 panel. First, Sverigedemokraterna is its
      own arm rather than part of a four-party cluster on the right.
      Second, Moderaterna and Kristdemokraterna are below the
      origin on PC2, separated from L and C which sit closer to the
      middle of PC2. Third, the red-green grouping (S, V, MP) is
      tighter than the equivalent grouping in 2022-26, because S and
      MP shared a cabinet for most of the mandate.
    </p>

    <h2>Where parties disagree most, 2018-22</h2>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/56_per_topic_stance_18_22.png`} alt="Per-topic vote stance, 2018-22, top 20 polarising topics" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Mean vote stance per (party, unified topic), top 20 topics
        by cross-party variance. Most cells sit in the yellow-green
        band: the chamber passes the majority of contested votes,
        and most parties vote Yes most of the time. The 2022-26
        equivalent figure (on the 2022-2026 page) shows substantially
        more red.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The 2018-22 chamber was less polarised than the 2022-26
      chamber by this measurement. Most party-topic cells sit in
      positive territory (Yes-leaning), with the main exceptions on
      Sverigedemokraterna's distinctive positions on rights and
      disability questions. The cluster pattern that defines the
      2022-26 chamber (V, MP and C on one side; M, KD, L, SD on the
      other) does not yet appear in 2018-22, because the L and C
      positions sit closer to the cabinet on most contested topics
      and SD is its own pole.
    </p>

    <h2>Vote versus reasoning</h2>

    <p>
      For every party pair we measured a vote-stance similarity from
      the chamber record and a reasoning similarity from
      topic-centred cosine between reservation reasoning vectors.
      In 2018-22 the reservation coverage is full (every party has
      reservation material in at least 26 of 28 topics), so no
      speech-based fallback is needed.
    </p>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/58_vote_vs_reasoning_18_22.png`} alt="Vote-versus-reasoning scatter, 2018-22" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        Each point is one party pair. Highlighted pairs: S-MP (the
        Löfven cabinet partners, top right, vote and reason alike);
        KD-M (Alliance partners, above-trend, vote and reason alike);
        M-SD (vote alike at 0.92 and reasoning at moderate positive
        similarity).
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Three pairs are worth naming. S-MP sit at the highest vote
      similarity (0.94) and the highest reasoning similarity (0.60)
      of any pair, consistent with their cabinet partnership through
      most of the mandate. KD-M sit at 0.95 vote and 0.37 reasoning,
      consistent with their Alliance partnership and shared
      opposition vocabulary. M-SD vote at 0.92 with reasoning at
      0.31, which is above the cross-pair trend line and indicates
      that the M-SD reasoning convergence was already underway
      during the previous mandate, even though the two parties did
      not yet form a bloc on the vote record.
    </p>

    <p>
      The most below-trend pairs in 2018-22 are S-L, V-M, MP-L,
      MP-KD and V-KD. These are pairs where the parties voted
      together on a substantial share of contested votes (typically
      because both supported the cabinet's legislation) but their
      reservation reasoning texts diverge sharply. None of these
      pairs survived into 2022-26 as named pairs in the 2022-26
      article; the coalition structure that produced them no longer
      exists.
    </p>

    <h2>Top behavioural defectors</h2>

    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}/figures/52_defectors_comparison.png`} alt="Top 12 behavioural defectors per mandate, side by side" loading="lazy" />
      <figcaption>
        The left panel shows the 2018-22 top 12. Most defectors are
        Vänsterpartiet members (Gudrun Nordborg, Jonas Sjöstedt,
        Hillevi Larsson and others) and Socialdemokrat MPs whose
        voting records sit closer to Miljöpartiet than to S.
        Liberalerna does not appear prominently.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      The 2018-22 defector pattern is not the L-defectors pattern of
      2022-26. The two Vänsterpartiet outliers (Gudrun Nordborg
      voting closer to "no party", reflecting independent positions;
      Jonas Sjöstedt with a longer parliamentary record) are
      individual cases rather than a caucus-level drift. The S-MP
      defectors are six MPs whose voting records sit closer to MP
      than to S, consistent with the cabinet partnership and the
      shared red-green agenda. The C-L pairs (Abir Al-Sahlani and
      Hanna Wagenius) are members of Centerpartiet whose votes look
      more like Liberalerna, consistent with the C-L closeness on
      the chamber map.
    </p>

    <p>
      None of the 2022-26 L-defectors (Gulan Avci, Lina Nordquist,
      Malin Danielsson, Martin Melin, Mauricio Rojas, Jakob
      Olofsgård, Helena Gellerman) appear on the 2018-22 list. The
      L-defectors phenomenon described in the 2022-2026 article is a
      property of the 2022-26 mandate specifically.
    </p>

    <h2>Stated and revealed, 2018-22</h2>

    <p>
      Using the same topic-matched methodology as the 2022-26
      article, we embedded each 2018 manifesto sentence into the
      same vector space as the 2018-22 reservation reasoning,
      assigned each sentence to its nearest unified topic, and
      compared within-(party, topic) cells. The headline pattern by
      party:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>SD: 0.70 mean across 15 topics.</strong> The
      highest topic-matched similarity in 2018-22. SD's 2018
      manifesto and its 2018-22 reservations describe policy in
      compatible language across the broadest range of topics.</li>
      <li><strong>M: 0.68 across 13 topics.</strong> Consistent
      across cycles; M's 2022 gap is also in this range.</li>
      <li><strong>V: 0.68 across 10 topics.</strong> Higher than
      V's 2022-26 gap of 0.61; the V manifesto in 2018 sat closer
      to V's reservation register than the 2022 manifesto does to
      V's 2022-26 register.</li>
      <li><strong>M: 0.68; MP: 0.65; KD: 0.66; L: 0.66; C: 0.63;
      S: 0.63.</strong> The remaining parties fall in a tight
      0.63 to 0.66 band.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The 2018-22 spread between parties is 0.063 (0.628 to 0.698).
      The 2022-26 spread is 0.150 (0.61 to 0.76). The eight parties'
      manifestos describe their parliamentary records more uniformly
      well in 2018-22 than in 2022-26, with the wider 2022-26 spread
      driven by L's rise to 0.76 (in cabinet, comparing manifesto
      against majority opinions) and V's fall to 0.61 (in
      opposition, comparing aspirational manifesto against
      technical reservations).
    </p>

    <h2>Reservations as a structural signal</h2>

    <p>
      Reservations are dissenting opinions filed by opposition
      parties on committee reports. Their count per (party, year) is
      a direct indicator of the party's role in the chamber that
      year. The longitudinal piece shows the trajectory; the
      mandate-specific story is that all four of M, KD, L and SD
      filed several hundred reservations per year in 2018-22,
      consistent with their opposition role. V also filed several
      hundred per year. C's count rose with the January Agreement
      arrangement. S and MP filed under 300 per year during the
      Löfven II cabinet, rising in 2021-22 as the cabinet
      composition changed.
    </p>

    <h2>What changed in 2022</h2>

    <p>
      The bloc transition between this mandate and the next is the
      subject of the longitudinal overview at
      <a href={`${base}/`}>the overview page</a>. The four short
      observations that anchor the comparison:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>The four Tidö parties (M, KD, L, SD) voted together on
      16 to 30 percent of contested chamber votes in 2018-22. The
      figure rose to 67 percent in 2022-23 and 98 percent in
      2025-26.</li>
      <li>L-M and L-KD per-year vote correlations were essentially
      zero throughout 2018-22 and jumped to 0.99+ at the start of
      2022-26.</li>
      <li>The L caucus's behavioural defectors (eight of the top
      twelve in 2022-26) did not exist as a measurable group in
      2018-22.</li>
      <li>Sverigedemokraterna's reservation count fell from 1,093
      in 2021-22 to 17 in 2025-26; the formal opposition register
      of Sverigedemokraterna in 2018-22 was abandoned during
      2022-26.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
      The 2022-2026 article describes the chamber that resulted from
      these changes; this article describes the chamber that
      preceded them. For a 2026 voter the two should be read
      together, because the parties on the September 2026 ballot
      are the same parties that produced both chambers.
    </p>

    <hr />

    <p class="method-note">
      Source data and methodology are documented on the
      <a href={`${base}/method`}>method page</a>. The unified
      topic clustering used throughout is documented at the
      <a href="https://github.com/freol35241/ps-sverige">project
      repository</a>. The 2018 manifestos are from the SND "Vi
      vill" archive; the chamber data is from
      <a href="https://data.riksdagen.se">data.riksdagen.se</a>.
    </p>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .method-note {
    font-size: 0.92rem;
    color: var(--ink-muted, #555);
  }
</style>
